        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our primary science goal is to detect 12CO(4-3) line to spatially resolve the molecular gas in the host galaxies of luminous quasars. The sensitivity is calculated so that a SN=5 is reached for the faintest object and is the same for all targets to make data comparable across the sample.

We will simultaneously detect the spatially resolved continuum emission from cold dust at 600 microns. Our choice of line is argued in the scientific justification, and is motivated by tracing the dense molecular gas (10**5 cm-3) associated with star formation as well as achieving good spatial resolution. The remaining three spectral windows will record continuum in three 1.875 GHz windows in 31 MHz (32 km/s) channels. The continuum flux is estimated from an SED fit to the SDSS and WISE photometry using a quasar SED from Polatto et al. (2007). Quasars were selected to be radio-quiet, and therefore the synchrotron flux at 600 microns will be negligible.

We expect the molecular gas to be resolved but not spread accross more than about 5 beams. The maximum recoverable scale corresponds to ~20kpc, no cold molecular gas is expected on such large scales, we therefore do not require use of the ACA. The field-of-view corresponds to ~100kpc, allowing us to cover the quasar host galaxy as well as any potential close companions.

We estimate the molecular gas mass using the following assumptions. Black hole mass derived from reverberation bases techniques re available from Shen et al. (2011). Using the relation between the black hole mass and bulge mass from Haring &amp; Rix (2004) we estimate the bulge mass which is a lower limit to the total galaxy mass. Assuming low gas fractions of 30%, which represents gas rich galaxies capable of triggering quasars (e.g. Bournaud et al. 2011, Hopkins et al. 2008), we estimate a cold gas masses of 2.7 x 10**12 Msun. Additionally, we calculate an accretion rate from the bolometric luminosities from Shen et al. (2011). Assuming a quasar lifetime of ~ 100 Myr (Yu &amp; Tremaine 2002) and a fuelling efficiency of 1%, we derive a gas mass of 7.0 x 10**10 Msun. Adopting the higher mass and using formulae from Bolatto et al. 2004 and a conservative XCO factor of 4 (Bolatto et al. 2004), we derive a lower limit to the line flux of 7.47 Jy km/s. Given the estimated line width from Gultekin et al. (2009), we reach a SN of 45 per resolution element and beam.

These requests ensure that even given the above described worst case scenario, we will be able to detect the CO and otherwise derive meaningful upper limits. In case of a non-detection, we will be able to place an upper limit on the cold gas mass of &lt;10**10 Msun by summing over the the line. Such a result would imply both very low gas fraction in these massive host galaxies and gas masses lower than the fuel supply of the quasars.

The three sources have similar science goals, but were split into different science goals due to the number of tunings required. While the expected source properties differ between objects, we aim for the same sensitivities to keep the data comparable between objects. We do not need observations with the ACA and have we no special requirements on bandpass accuracy, data rates, scheduling or calibration.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
