    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Quasars are amongst the most luminous objects in the universe. Over their lifetimes, they require gas supplies comparable with that of their host galaxy. This fuel needs to lose of a majority of its angular momentum on time scales considerably shorter than the dynamical time scale of the host galaxies. Major mergers of gas-rich galaxies as well as cold flows onto gas rich disks that trigger violent disk instabilities could provide the strong external disturbances to enable quasar fuelling. Both mechanisms will lead to heavily disturbed systems with irregular morphology and disturbed kinematics. We propose an ALMA pilot study to map dense molecular gas (CO 4-3) with high-resolution (~1kpc) in a sample of three luminous z~0.6 quasars. The quasars are also being imaged as part of an approved HST campaign (PI Villforth), allowing us to combine the ALMA view of the cold molecular gas with a detailed view of the stellar morphology. This will help us understand how cold gas and stars are connected in systems that are expected to have large fuelling flows towards the center.</prp:abstract>
